column1: What will be The We Company's (WeWork's parent company) end-of-day market capitalization on the day of its initial public offering (IPO)?
column4: The We Company will not have an IPO before 30 November 2019
column5: ['Less than $10 billion', 'Between $10 billion and $25 billion, inclusive', 'More than $25 billion but less than $40 billion', '$40 billion or more', 'The We Company will not have an IPO before 30 November 2019']
column6: ['Business', 'Finance']

Given the recent negative news press, SoftBank refinancing, and public ally announced strategy shift which will take time to implement, Wework will not be ready by 11/30, not to mention the substantial securities documentation work required and likely corporate governance overhaul.
PE Bubble will not pop all at once.
With prospective market valuations and opinions appearing to vary from between $15 to 49 Bn and current losses there is a need for a period of reassessment which cannot be completed before 1 Nov 19

The events leading up to the original timeline of their IPO has spooked prospective public market investors. Can't imagine they get this off at a valuation that pleases their private owners (cough cough SOFTBANK).
Cause I know

I have never seen such a barrage of comment in the financial media about what a worthless lump of nothing this is even without Neumann and revising the share profile. Cannot see this getting away in a public market at all. The main people who want out - Son and his KSA clients - have other problems as well.
Looks to have huge financial issues.
We Company has an excessive private valuation and no clear path to profitability. Overall governance problems are ingrained, but there is a push by controlling investors to go public.
I was wrong initially, The bottom has completely fallen out of this IPO
Recent developments and departure of CEO.

From the Economist: “ WeWork, which provides shared office space, said it would scrap its initial public offering. Last week the company, once considered one of America’s most valuable start-ups, ousted its chief executive, Adam Neumann. It had previously delayed its flotation amid concern from investors—including SoftBank, its biggest—about its management and burgeoning losses.”
https://mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idUSKBN1WF1NS

Today's WSJ headline confirmed what a redoubled analysis showed - that they are "out of cash", and in severe and extended need of organizational restructure. WE Company is filing application with the SEC to withdraw the IPO filing.
IPO withdrawn, some reports it's just postponed, but also buzz of bankruptcy. Founder Adam Neumann cashed out $700M, this seems to be the new way to make money.
Darn. Forgot to check crowd. Which was more all in than I was. Poo...
It has a burn rate of $219,000 per hour. Staggering losses.

A less-than $10 billion mkt cap means SoftBank has to recognize a $30 billion valuation "loss" - so I think they would prefer to avoid crystallizing that in the minds of investors & lenders, and calling into question the value of their other positions, and further calling into question their judgment/acumen. But if they absolutely need the money - reputation be damned. So 1% to reflect that.
Reminiscent of Robinhood's disruption of FinTech, and Über and Lyft in transportation.

From the Economist: “ The Financial Times reported that WeWork, a loss-making provider of shared-office space, has halted the signing of new lease agreements to rein in costs. The company pulled an initial public offering last week because of investor fears that it was overvalued and that Adam Neumann, its co-founder, was out of control. On Tuesday he was ousted as chief executive”
Strong financial pressure for IPO before end of year... but I strongly suspect current shake-down of governance and financials mean an IPO will not happen before 30 Nov.

Whelp I misread this one. Thought SoftBank would try to salvage, but they seems pretty committed to trimming down the business and selling non-core subsidiaries. Such drastic changes can’t support an IPO by the end of November

There are only two months until the end of this challenge. The financial press is now reporting that a large layoff may be coming soon. A head count reduction would conserve capital, and thus delay the need to raise new money through an IPO.

SoftBank announced a $1B injection of funding, This will a) help stabilize WeWork while they get the new CEO producing and b) instill greater confidence in SoftBank investors on the hopes of a company turnaround. IPO gets delayed at least one more business quarter.

This is one almighty mess and at present I cannot see the ipo going forward - sheer disconnect between private and public market valuation - ceo being pushed out - core investor concerned about losing face - public markets increasing levels of scrutiny for flashy tech companies who burn cash and are unable to point to future profits any time soon dampening overall appetite - wall street implies valuation between $12bn &15bn - the optics of this whole scenario are shockingly bad
Saw what the crowd had to say...
Why would it NOT have an IPO before 30 Nov? Because the offer is in disarray, the leadership seems to be floundering and the CEO has just stepped down to take a back seat after a no-confidence vote.

If you Google WeWork you can find any number of articles regarding the company's valuation. I've read several pieces in the financial press that say the value has fallen by about two thirds, from $47B to somewhere in the neighborhood of $15B. The CEO agreed to step down to become the non-executive chairman, after pressure from investors. It seems this was done to try to salvage the IPO. The company needs an infusion of capital or it will have to halt expansion plans.
Neumann has stepped down as CEO, with two executives who reported to him taking over as co-CEOs [1,2,4].

Nudging towards No IPO before November 30th due to CEO stepping down news. While new management may be better for the company in the long term, it would appear they need to do some damage control before potential IPO.

Neumann blinked. But "co-CEOs"? "Ratchet provision'? A valuation that keeps weakening - now I read "$15 billion" - seems generous by today's standards. If the economy rolls over in 2020, the WeWork thesis gets tested - at a time of attenuated capital levels and funding sources for WeWork to tap. Seems like strong headwinds for an IPO.
New CEO search process means there is no way the IPO can happen in the stated timeframe.
Seems impossible within this timeframe after the CEO stepped down. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/business/dealbook/wework-ceo-adam-neumann.html?action=click&module=Top%20Stories&pgtype=Homepage

- $1.5B in revenue ending Q2 2019; $1.37B in loss sme period - Softbank is large investor - needs an IPO to keep it going to raise cash. - CEO unpopular - SoftBank wants him out. A replacement with a seasoned CEO could stabilize an IPO. - WeWork recently reduced their IPO target valuation frm $47B to $20 - $30B - Flexible office space grew YOY 7.6 to 86% - more competitors entering the space - They are in a line of business that has ease of entry - nothing special about them - I suspect huge pressure for Neumann to step aside so that the IPO can go through - too much money on the line to wait it out. - Compared to BXP which is profitable with similar revenues and at a $20B market cap, I place WeWork going IPO and landing under $20B on day 1
14-21 days.

The latest fight between the board of directors and the CEO will delay the IPO indefinitely. If the CEO wants to make money he will step aside and the IPO will be accelerated, but the company will need to show more solid fundamentals before they prepare a new filing, and that will take time.
THey post phoned the IPO TOUR? What is there product? Furnished offices?
Softbank seeking to remove WE's CEO after a very bad news week for WeWork's Neumann. Neumann has the votes - but SoftBank has the money. Who will blink?
They are not looking so good and may want to wait
~14 days.

The market rejected the $40-50bn valuation and so it is not possible to be $40bn or more. Dropping a valuation by far more than 50% would be unprecedented, so far less than $20bn is unlikely. Realistically it will go public next year or the following year after the devastating defeat.

SoftBank is encouraging WeWork to postpone til next year. WeWork is going to hold off until 10/19, but 1.5 months is enough to get the IPO going. I am becoming less confident in the $25-40bn and more confident in postponing, but WeWork needs cash and waiting will not likely result in an improving economic environment
Company needs to get it's sh.. strait before it goes public. Going to take until current tax year has ended to roll off some unwanted debts.

It seems in recent reports (https://www.wsj.com/articles/wework-parent-expected-to-postpone-ipo-11568671322) are showing that WeWork is postponing it's IPO. With the attention this company is getting, there could be more issues that delay an IPO. However, the companies founders may have too much invested to delay again, thus I could see a market cap around where some other recent IPOs have landed (Uber, SmileDirect) on day 1.

too much bad publicity and too many aspects to get 'right' before investor confidence is right - September results could just revive it but let's see..... There's still significant financial pressure to float before end of year but at this stage I'm just not confident of it being before December.

IPO was reported delayed in NYT earlier in the week from corporate governance matters to weak financial prospects. It may be wiser to forego an IPO and remain private given the weak market valuations.

I think there's a lot for them to work out yet, seems their valuations maybe were based on false confidence in the past and I'll repeat what others have said about having to justify their valuation estimates. Too high and they'll crash out, too low and maybe confidence in the company wouldn't be as high as they'd like. Finding the balance (historical losses, future plans) will be the biggest challenge so I'm not even sure an IPO will be secured by November this year. It could be back to the drawing board for a while until a more solid plan has been worked out? P/L seems shaky, I'd want more time to build a watertight future plan at least.
Announced they are delaying the IPO. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/17/business/dealbook/wework-ipo.html
They have already delayed to Oct, it could easily get delayed further since 1 month typically isn't enough time to convince prospective investors in the context of an IPO.
We Company confirmed the IPO will be delayed:
IPO delayed. Company said they expect to do it "before the end of the year" Latest numbers mentioned around the $10 billion mark.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wework-ipo/wework-parent-says-ipo-still-on-despite-setbacks-idUSKBN1W12T6 Seems increasingly unlikely they'll go out before December at the earliest, but stay tuned.
Adjusting based on recent wsj article

Stories in the news support an initial ipo of 10-20 as a starting market cap. IPOs tend to go up in the first day of trading. Many are asking for the company to back-off from their IPO, but that does not seem to be a common occurrence.
Softbank announced 9-13-19 that it would buy $750MM of the new issue - which is estimated to be 25% of the new float.
Mostly basing this off of previous forecasts, as well as the fact that The We Company seems to be losing public confidence and there's a call for it to pull the IPO.
Source: https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2019/09/13/1568385712000/WeWrite-down/

In a normal world this would be pulled, but the major investor who loses is Softbank and no one else cares. Plus they need an IPO to have access to a $6 billion credit facility, and they're talking about accepting a $10 billion valuation to get that done. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wework-ipo-valuation/exclusive-wework-considers-ipo-valuation-of-as-low-as-10-billion-sources-idUSKCN1VY1PB

Based on cafebedouin reminder about Softbank investment - the aggregate estimated valuation vis-a-vis Softbank's investment aren't adding up to me. The supermajority changes in governance don't seem to be enough. Wall Street is falling way out of love with the prior internal valuation of $40 billion to $50 billion - estimates this morning are $10 billiion (?!) All of this moves the chance of a pulled IPO.
Questionable business model. While the founder has cleaned up disturbing issues regarding payments and super-voting shares, I think his past poor judgement will depress the IPO pricing.
They need money, but they are not at the right valuation to get it from the stock market.
WeWork just announced the IPO is scheduled for Sept 23. Analysts expectations are for less than or equal to $20bn. Will update when I hear more
This will take place and the value is borderline 10 billion

A wild ride - I thought WeWork was estimated north of $50 billion - and yet I read today estimates as "low" as $18 billion, with trouble floating debt to cover cash drain. I also read of regulatory irregularities regarding self-dealing with the founder. Thus, adding a chance that the IPO is pulled b/c of either lack of debt market support or SEC compliance issues.
Revising up due to Softbanks guidance suggesting WeWork postpone
The lead investor (Softbank) has a habit of 100-200% overvaluation
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wework-ipo/wework-presses-on-with-ipo-pushing-softbank-into-a-corner-idUSKCN1VV07C
SoftBank now urging to shelve IPO

From the FT. "Advisors for the We Company were said to still be testing investor appetite at a valuation of between $15bn and $20bn, according to people briefed on the matter. That is far below the $47bn valuation given to WeWork when SoftBank invested $2bn in the business this year."
https://www.ft.com/content/111f8e00-d346-11e9-8367-807ebd53ab77

High expenses, heavy recession risks, governance and conflict of interest claims, and a low path to profitability. As pointed out in this article (https://seekingalpha.com/article/4289610-wework-one-worst-ipos-2019) WeWorks most similar competitor is valued at only $4bn. This competitor (IWG) also has a rev/sq ft that’s about 23% higher than WeWork.

Bloomberg TV is discussing this issues extensively. It has been said that a minority assume that less than 10 Billion market capitalization is only justified, because long term engagement of WeWork with short term leasing is highly risky. WeWork is not profitable up to now. The world economy slowed and the US economy is at the end of a cycle with signs of weaknesses, too. On the opposite is SoftBank the biggest holder of investments at WeWork and seeing opportunities on long run. I assume that decides.
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wework-ipo-exclusive/exclusive-wework-to-press-on-with-ipo-launch-despite-valuation-concerns-sources-idUSKCN1VR2L6

Current estimates value the company at around USD 20 billion. That is around 30 billion less than the 47 billion established in the last private financing round. Question is then should the IPO go forward, with a recession also on the horizon.
